Thanks for the detailed reproduction — this is a real issue in Skia's PNG codec.

The root cause is that Skia reads all PNG chunks before IDAT (the actual pixel data) in 4KB increments during codec creation. A ~100MB Exif chunk means ~25,000 read iterations before decoding even begins. It's not truly hanging — it's processing extremely slowly with no size guard or cancellation mechanism.

Here's a workaround you can use now: since you're already using Magick.NET to create the images, strip or limit the Exif metadata size before passing the stream to SkiaSharp:

```csharp
// Strip exif before decoding with SkiaSharp
using var image = new MagickImage(stream);
image.RemoveProfile("exif");
var cleaned = new MemoryStream();
image.Write(cleaned, MagickFormat.Png);
cleaned.Seek(0, SeekOrigin.Begin);

using var codec = SKCodec.Create(cleaned);
var bitmap = SKBitmap.Decode(codec);
```

Alternatively, you could pre-validate PNG chunk sizes by reading the chunk headers before passing to SkiaSharp, and reject files with excessively large metadata.

We'll investigate whether a managed-side guard can be added to SKCodec.Create to bound metadata processing time.
